<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920211-0041</DOCNO><DOCID>920211-0041.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- B.A.T Industries PLC:   Brown andamp; Williamson to Use   More Warning Labels Abroad</HL><DATE>02/11/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   BTI</CO><MS>CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><RE>EUROPE (EU)KENTUCKY (KY)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   Brown andamp; Williamson Tobacco Corp. said it will puthealth-warning labels on cigarette packages for sale incountries where the packs don't have warning labels yet.   The move comes as other U.S. tobacco makers contemplatesimilar labeling steps. Last week, Philip Morris Cos., thelargest tobacco manufacturer, was reported to be ready tobegin such a labeling effort, and RJR Nabisco Holdings Inc.,parent of R.J. Reynolds Tobacco, said it was contemplatingthe move. But as with Philip Morris, Brown andamp; Williamson'schange would cover a relatively small part of internationalsales, since many countries already have health warningsrequirements.</LP><TEXT>   A spokesman for Brown andamp; Williamson, Louisville, Ky., saidmore than 90% of its cigarettes sold overseas already carrysome type of health warning, so its plan would only pertainto the balance. He said 40% of unit volume is ininternational products, representing about a 20% market sharein overseas cigarette sales among U.S. companies.   The company, a unit of Britain's B.A.T Industries PLC,said it would begin putting the notices on packs later thisyear.</TEXT></DOC>